yae ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">reversed? 1 Chron. 17:1-4; 22:7, 8. </div><div class="t m3e0 x5d h2f yb0c ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">NOTE.—The </div><div class="t ma8 xf he y1cd ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">fact that the prophet Nathan spoke words of approval to the </div><div class="t m778 x17 he y8ee ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">plan of the king, a plan that seemed to be prompted by unselfish love for God, </div><div class="t m113c x17 he y1269 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">and that would glorify Him, should not lessen confidence in the counsel of a </div><div class="t m1499 x17 he y661 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">prophet. Rather, the fact that his imperfect judgment was so soon corrected, </div><div class="t m55b x11 he y286 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">and that he faithfully delivered the message of God as soon as it came to him, </div><div class="t m694 x11 he y39f ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">should deepen our confidence in the prophetic words. </div><div class="t m2a39 x6c he y153a ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The Prophets&apos; Relation to Rulers </div><div class="t m41c x48 he ya2f ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">13. </div><div class="t me9a xc he ya2f ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">What responsibility often rested upon the prophet in his relation to </div><div class="t m16f x17 he y46e ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the leaders of God&apos;s people? 2 Sam. 24:11-14; 1 Chron. 21:18; 2 Chron. </div><div class="t maf2 x17 he yfe6 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">33:18. </div><div class="t m41c x48 he y3d6 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">14. </div><div class="t m87c xc he y217 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">What notable instance is recorded, illustrating the prophet&apos;s faith-</div><div class="t mff x17 he y4af ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">ful discharge of his duty to bring messages of reproof to the king? When </div><div class="t m55c x11 he yf6f ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the reproof was accepted, what cheering message did the Lord send? 2 Sam. </div><div class="t m760 x11 he y2a4 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">12:1-7, 13. </div><div clas